{"title_page": "Lego Minifigures (theme)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{about|the 2010\u2013present [[Lego]] theme|the toy figurines|Lego minifigure}}\n{{Infobox Lego theme\n|name         = Minifigures\n|image        = [[File:Minifigures Logo.png|200px]]\n|subthemes    =\n|parentthemes =\n|subject      = Collectible [[minifigure]]s\n|from         = 2010\n|to           = present\n|sets         = 517 minifigures (31 series)\n|characters   = Various, such as from sports, history, popular culture, etc.\n|website      = http://minifigures.lego.com/\n}}\n'''Minifigures''' is a 2010 [[Lego]] [[Lego theme|theme]] based on a set of collectible Lego [[minifigure]]s. Each figure is an original character with new clothing and facial designs, and most contain previously unseen accessories. Each series usually contain 16 different minifigures, however some series contain as few as 9 minifigures, while others contain up to 22.\n\n==Details==\nThe series consists of a number of individually themed collectible Lego minifigures based on movies, sports, history, and popular culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shop.lego.com/Product/?p=8683|title=LEGO Minifigures|publisher=[[Lego shop]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100729192722/http://shop.lego.com/Product/?p=8683|archivedate=29 July 2010}}</ref> The figures are sold individually in sealed, unmarked packets, giving customers a random chance at obtaining any particular figurine. While considered a novel approach by some, it has raised controversy amongst enthusiasts and collectors, increasing the amount of difficulty in obtaining a complete collection{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}. Purchases from many retailers make no guarantees regarding the contents of a particular packet. Despite attempts to obfuscate the contents of these packets, the bags of Series 1 and 2 have a second figurine-specific bar code on the rear of the packet, next to the EAN/UPC product bar code (which is unique to each series). This has allowed customers to identify individual figures within the packet, significantly decreasing the amount of money and effort required to obtain a complete collection, and eliminates the possibility of unintentionally receiving duplicates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bricks.inof.de/docs/minifig-barcodes/index-en.html|title=Barcodes of the Collectible Minifigures|publisher=bricks.inof.de}}</ref> There are also apps for both [[iPhone]] and [[Android (operating system)|Android]] devices that utilize these bar codes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.betterthantomorrow.com/minicollector|title=Mini Collector|date=30 August 2010|access-date=17 January 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101003125137/http://blog.betterthantomorrow.com/minicollector/|archive-date=3 October 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLego has eliminated the figurine-specific bar codes on all Series 3 and 4 packets and replaced them with a braille-like system of dots embossed in the lower seal of the bag. In theory, this will allow customers to continue identifying the figure enclosed within.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fbtb.net/2010/11/18/series-3-blind-pack-code-cracked/|title=Dot codes for US Series 3|publisher=fbtb.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.betterthantomorrow.com/2011/08/05/lego-minifigures-series-5-the-codes/|title=Dot codes sheet for LEGO Minifigures Series 5|date=5 August 2011|access-date=28 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820140010/https://blog.betterthantomorrow.com/2011/08/05/lego-minifigures-series-5-the-codes/|archive-date=20 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Later series do not have any markings to indicate their contents.\n\nOn average a new series has been released every four months. Release dates sometimes vary between countries.\n\n==Sets==\nThe numbering of the figures in each set below is in accordance with the visual guide sheet which is included within the individual packets for each series.\n\n===Series 1===\n[[File:LEGO Minifigures Series 1.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 16 units in Series 1]]\nSeries 1 (set number: 8683) was first released on 5 March 2010 in the United Kingdom and was released on 4 June 2010 in the United States. The first series consists the following units:<ref>{{cite web|title=Collectable Minifigures: Series 01|url=https://brickset.com/sets/theme-Collectable-Minifigures/subtheme-Series-01|website=Brickset|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" style=\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1em;\"  | #\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Minifigure\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Accessories\n! class=\"unsortable\"  | Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Tribe (Native American)|Tribal]] [[Hunting|Hunter]]||[[Bow and arrow]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to \"Indians\" Lego Western sub-theme.\n|-\n|2\n|[[Cheerleading|Cheerleader]]||[[Pom-pom]] (2)||First appearance of the Lego pom-pom piece.\n|-\n|3\n|[[Caveman]]||[[Club (weapon)|Club]]||First appearance of the Lego Caveman hair piece.\n|-\n|4\n|[[Circus clown]]||[[Vehicle horn|Bicycle horn]]||First appearance of the Lego Afro hair piece.\n|-\n|5\n|[[Zombie]]||[[Chicken as food|Chicken leg]], [[Shovel]]||\n|-\n|6\n|[[Skateboarding|Skater]]||[[Skateboard]]||\n|-\n|7\n|[[Robot]]||||First appearance of the Lego Robot helmet piece.\n|-\n|8\n|[[Crash test dummy|Demolition Dummy]]||[[Wrench]], [[Licence plate|License plate]]|| \n|-\n|9\n|[[Magic (illusion)|Magician]]||[[Wand]]||Comes with additional hair piece.\n|-\n|10\n|[[Lucha libre|Super Wrestler]]|||| \n|-\n|11\n|[[Nursing|Nurse]]||[[Clipboard]], [[Hypodermic needle|Needle]]|| \n|-\n|12\n|[[Ninja]]||[[Katana]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Ninja\" Lego Castle sub-theme.\n|-\n|13\n|[[Astronaut|Spaceman]]||[[Raygun]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Classic Space\" Lego Space sub-theme.\n|-\n|14\n|Forestman||Bow and arrow||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Forestmen\" Lego Castle sub-theme, and by extension [[Robin Hood]].\n|-\n|15\n|[[Scuba diving|Deep Sea Diver]]||||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Divers\" Lego Town sub-theme.\n|-\n|16\n|[[Cowboy]]||[[Revolver]] (2)||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Cowboys\" Lego Western sub-theme.\n|}\n\n===Series 2===\n[[File:LEGO Minifigures Series 2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 16 units in Series 2]]\nSeries 2 (set number: 8684) was first released on 2 September 2010 in both the United Kingdom and the United States. The second series consists of the following units:<ref>{{cite web|title=Collectable Minifigures: Series 02|url=https://brickset.com/sets/theme-Collectable-Minifigures/subtheme-Series-02|website=Brickset|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" style=\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1em;\"  | #\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Minifigure\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Accessories\n! class=\"unsortable\"  | Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Mariachi|Maraca Man]]||[[Maraca]] (2)||First appearances of the Lego [[Sombrero]], [[Maraca]], and [[Poncho]] pieces.\n|-\n|2\n|[[Spartan army|Spartan Warrior]]||[[Spear]], [[Shield]]||First appearance of the Lego Spartan helmet and new spear piece.\n|-\n|3\n|[[Ringmaster (circus)|Ringmaster]]||[[Whip]]|| \n|-\n|4\n|[[Witchcraft|Witch]]||[[Broom]]|| \n|-\n|5\n|[[Vampire]]||[[Bat]]||This minifigure design would later be reused by Lord Vampyre for the \"Monster Fighters\" Lego theme.\n|-\n|6\n|[[Traffic police|Traffic Cop]]||[[Traffic ticket|Ticket]], [[Handcuffs]]|| \n|-\n|7\n|[[Exploration|Explorer]]||[[Binoculars]], [[Magnifying glass]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to Lord Sam Sinister and the \"Adventurers\" Lego theme. Based on an explorer during the [[Scramble for Africa]].\n|-\n|8\n|[[Lifeguard]]||[[Rescue buoy]]||First appearance of the Lego [[Rescue buoy]] piece.\n|-\n|9\n|[[Mime artist|Mime]]||||First appearance of the Lego Beret piece. Comes with 2 other heads for different expressions.\n|-\n|10\n|[[Olympic weightlifting|Weight Lifter]]||[[Dumbbell]]||First appearance of the Lego weight piece.\n|-\n|11\n|Pop [[Celebrity|Star]]||[[Microphone]]||First appearance of the Lego microphone and Pop Star hair piece. Modeled after [[Britney Spears]].\n|-\n|12\n|[[Cross-country skiing|Skier]]||[[Ski]] (2), [[Ski pole]] (2)||First appearance of the Lego Winter cap piece.\n|-\n|13\n|[[Disco]] Dude||[[Gramophone record|Record disc]] case|| \n|-\n|14\n|[[Karate]] [[Sensei|Master]]||[[Trophy]]||First appearance of the Lego trophy piece, later reused for nanofigures.\n|-\n|15\n|[[Surfing|Surfer]]||[[Surfboard]]|| \n|-\n|16\n|[[Pharaoh]]||[[Sceptre|Staff]]|| \n|}\n\n===Series 3===\n[[File:LEGO Minifigures Series 3.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The 16 units in Series 3]]\nSeries 3 (set number: 8803) was first released on 14 January 2011 in both the United Kingdom and the United States. The third series consists of the following units:<ref>{{cite web|title=Collectable Minifigures: Series 03|url=https://brickset.com/sets/theme-Collectable-Minifigures/subtheme-Series-03|website=Brickset|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" style=\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1em;\"  | #\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Minifigure\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Accessories\n! class=\"unsortable\"  | Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Fisherman]]||[[Fishing rod]], Fish||\n|-\n|2\n|[[Aircraft pilot|Pilot]]||||\n|-\n|3\n|[[Tribal chief]]||[[Spear]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Indians\" Lego Western sub-theme.\n|-\n|4\n|[[Samurai]] [[Warrior]]||[[Katana]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Ninja\" Lego Castle sub-theme.\n|-\n|5\n|[[Snowboarding|Snowboarder]]||[[Snowboard]]|| \n|-\n|6\n|[[Cyborg|Space Villain]]||[[Raygun]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Blacktron Future Generation\" Lego Space sub-theme. \n|-\n|7\n|[[Rikishi|Sumo Wrestler]]||[[Trophy]]||First appearance of the Lego Bun hair piece. \n|-\n|8\n|[[Mummy (undead)|Mummy]]||[[Scorpion]]||First Minifigure in the series to have arm and back printing.\n|-\n|9\n|[[Elves in fantasy fiction and games|Elf]]||[[Longbow]], [[Shield]]||First appearance of the Lego Elf short hair piece.\n|-\n|10\n|[[Tennis]] Player||[[Racket (sports equipment)|Tennis racket]]||First appearance of the Lego Tennis racket piece.\n|-\n|11\n|[[Auto racing|Race Car Driver]]|||| \n|-\n|12\n|[[Gorilla suit]] Guy||Banana||A Minifigure in a gorilla suit.\n|-\n|13\n|[[Extraterrestrial life|Space Alien]]||Raygun||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Alien Conquest\" Lego Space sub-theme.\n|-\n|14\n|[[Hula]] Dancer||[[Maraca]] (2)||First appearance of the Lego long wavy hair and hula skirt pieces.\n|-\n|15\n|[[Rapping|Rapper]]||[[Boombox]], [[Microphone]]|| \n|-\n|16\n|[[Baseball]] Player||[[Baseball bat]]||First appearance of the Lego bat piece.\n|}\n\n===Series 4===\nSeries 4 (set number: 8804) was first released on 1 April 2011 all around the world. The fourth series consists of the following units:<ref>{{cite web|title=Collectable Minifigures: Series 04|url=https://brickset.com/sets/theme-Collectable-Minifigures/subtheme-Series-04|website=Brickset|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" style=\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1em;\"  | #\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Minifigure\n! style=\"width:20em;\" | Accessories\n! class=\"unsortable\"  | Notes\n|-\n|1\n|[[Garden gnome|Lawn Gnome]]||[[Fishing rod]]|| \n|-\n|2\n|[[Kimono]] [[Geisha|Girl]]||[[Hand fan]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Ninja\" Lego Castle sub-theme. First appearance of the Lego fan piece.\n|-\n|3\n|[[Musketeer]]||[[Rapier]]||First appearance of the Lego rapier piece.\n|-\n|4\n|[[Punk rock]]er||Electric guitar||First appearance of the Lego [[Mohawk hairstyle|Mohawk]] hair and guitar pieces.\n|-\n|5\n|[[Surfing|Surfer]] Girl||[[Surfboard]]||A female variant of the Surfer (Series 2).\n|-\n|6\n|[[Vikings|Viking]]||[[Battle axe]], [[Shield]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Vikings\" Lego theme.\n|-\n|7\n|The [[Monster]]||||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Studios\" Lego theme. Modeled after [[Frankenstein's monster]].\n|-\n|8\n|[[Ice hockey|Hockey]] Player||[[Hockey stick]], [[Hockey puck]]||First appearance of the Lego hockey stick and helmet pieces.\n|-\n|9\n|[[Street skating|Street Skater]]||[[Skateboard]]|| \n|-\n|10\n|Sailor||[[Telescope]]||First appearance of the Lego sailor hat piece.\n|-\n|11\n|Soccer Player||[[Trophy]]|| \n|-\n|12\n|[[Werewolf]]||[[Bone]]||The minifigure reuses a recolored Lego elf short hair piece in dark brown.\n|-\n|13\n|[[Hazmat suit|Hazmat]] Guy||[[Sprayer|Spray]] gun||First appearance of the Lego Hazmat suit piece. \n|-\n|14\n|Artist||[[Paintbrush]], [[Palette (painting)|Palette]]||First appearance of the Lego paintbrush and palette pieces.\n|-\n|15\n|[[Ice skating|Ice Skater]]||||First appearance of the Lego ice-skate piece.\n|-\n|16\n|[[Mad scientist|Crazy Scientist]]||[[Laboratory flask|Flask]]||This minifigure is a direct reference to the \"Studios\" Lego theme. First appearance of the Lego [[Erlenmeyer flask]] and mad scientist hair pieces.\n|}\n\n===Series 5===\nSeries 5 (set number: 8805) was first released on 22 August 2011 in the United Kingdom and the United States. The fifth series consists of the following units:<ref>{{cite web|title=Collectable Minifigures: Series 05|url=https://brickset.com/sets/theme-Collectable-Minifigures/subtheme-Series-05|website=Brickset|accessdate=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%; text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\" style=\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:1em;\"  | #\n! style=\"width:15em;\" | Minifigure\n! style=\"width:20em;\"